<subSubSection id="C36F6539FF864469EE866E92FAE7FEBB" pageId="21" pageNumber="222" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8BCA36B2FF864469EE866E92FAE7FEBB" blockId="21.[151,1437,151,321]" pageId="21" pageNumber="222">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF864469EE866E92FEC3FF4B" bold="true" box="[199,317,151,177]" pageId="21" pageNumber="222">Remarks:</emphasis>
Recent collections of 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D31FF864469EC786E92FD3DFF4B" box="[569,707,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Hepialidae" genus="Abantiades" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="222" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paradoxa">
<emphasis id="B901EAA0FF864469EC786E92FD3DFF4B" box="[569,707,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="222">A. paradoxa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have increased specimen records, but the species is still not well represented in collections. Though the male was described in 1932, it was not until 2014 that the first female was collected near Merredin (WA) by NT. A second female was collected near the Brookton Highway 
<quantity id="4C8D9B57FF864469EB496EDAFAAFFF03" box="[1288,1361,223,249]" metricMagnitude="4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.9" pageId="21" pageNumber="222" unit="km" value="49.0">49 km</quantity>
SE of Kelmscott by PK on 
<date id="FFCB1072FF864469EF3E6F06FDEBFEE7" box="[383,533,258,285]" pageId="21" pageNumber="222" value="2016-05-06">
6 
<superScript id="7C009BFAFF864469EFCC6F07FE64FEEA" attach="left" box="[397,410,258,272]" fontSize="6" pageId="21" pageNumber="222">th</superScript>
May 2016
</date>
, as illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE44B43FF864469EC946F06FC71FEE7" author="Simonsen, T. J." box="[725,911,259,285]" pageId="21" pageNumber="222" refId="ref13172" refString="Simonsen, T. J. (2018) Splendid Ghost Moths and their Allies, A Revision of Australian Abantiades, Oncopera, Aenetus, Archaeoaenetus and Zelotypia (Hepialidae). In: Monographs on Australian Lepidoptera. Vol. 12. CSIRO Publishing, Melbourne, pp. 1 - 300. https: // doi. org / 10.1071 / 9781486307487" type="book" year="2018">Simonsen (2018</bibRefCitation>
: Pl. 33 Fig. C), further females have since been collected by PK (
<figureCitation id="134E2A37FF864469EF186F22FE53FEBB" box="[345,429,294,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="21.[151,250,1571,1595]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,345,1547]" captionTargetId="figure-115@21.[151,1436,345,1547]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURE 15. Abantiades paradoxa—(a) male and female adult moths from (b) and (c) Metro Road habitat." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6521700" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6521700/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="222">Fig. 15</figureCitation>
). The scale-like setae found on the external genitalia of the female are unique.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
